{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516341"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.06,0.04,0.05,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5091"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3679"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4748"},{"type":"tags","id":"4762"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the sexual health clinic with three days history of pain while urinating and a yellow-coloured urethral discharge. He had unprotected anal intercourse with a new male partner about a week ago. He has no anorectal symptoms. He denies any history of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) and has no significant medical history. On examination, the patient is uncomfortable and there is a moderate amount of mucopurulent discharge from the urethral meatus. The appropriate swabs are collected for testing and the patient agrees to return later for the results of the tests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular ceftriaxone and oral doxycycline","Oral cefixime and oral azithromycin","Intramuscular gentamicin and oral azithromycin","Intravenous penicillin G and oral azithromycin","Intramuscular ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with classical symptoms and signs of Neisseria gonorrhoea infection, which is one of the most common STIs in Australia, especially in men who have sex with men. This patient has presented with symptoms and signs related to the urogenital tract that includes, but is not limited to dysuria and penile discharge. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular ceftriaxone with oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended first-line treatment for gonorrhoea as it is highly effective and has a low risk of resistance. The recommended dose is 500mg as a single intramuscular injection, a second antibiotic (such as azithromycin) is also usually added to the regimen which is usually given as 1g stat per oral for uncomplicated genital and anorectal infection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf follow-up cannot be ensured for the patient to return for his test results, it would be prudent to commence treatment for both gonorrhoea and chlamydia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDoxycycline usually replaces azithromycin in the treatment regimen in the presence of rectal co-infection with chlamydia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular ceftriaxone and oral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E cover Neisseria gonorrhoea and Chlamydia trachomatis. However, doxycycline needs to be taken for seven days, and it may cause gastrointestinal side effects and photosensitivity. Therefore, this combination is not the first-line treatment of choice, but it can be considered in patients with a contraindication to azithromycin or in the presence of macrolide resistance. This is the preferred treatment if chlamydia co-infection, especially rectal co-infection with chlamydia is known or suspected. Doxycycline should be continued for 21 days if patient is symptomatic with anorectal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral cefixime and oral azithromycin \u003C/strong\u003Ealso cover Neisseria gonorrhoeae and Chlamydia trachomatis, and it is an alternative first-line treatment for Neisseria gonorrhoea infection. However, cefixime is not the preferred option due to the increasing resistance of Neisseria gonorrhoeae to this antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular gentamicin and oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended for the treatment of urethritis caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae. Gentamicin does not have good activity against this organism, and its use is associated with the risk of nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous penicillin G and oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended regimens for the treatment of gonorrhoea, especially because of the high prevalence of penicillin-resistant strains of Neisseria gonorrhoeae. Therefore, this combination is not the first-line treatment of choice for urethritis caused by this organism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intramuscular ceftriaxone with oral azithromycin is the first-line treatment of choice for gonorrhoea infection."],"references":["Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine. Gonorrhoea. In: Australian STI Management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/gonorrhoea","Ong JJ, Bourne C, Dean JA, Ryder N, Cornelisse VJ, Murray S, Kenchington P, Moten A, Gibbs C, Maunsell S, Davis T, Michaels J, Medland NA. Australian sexually transmitted infection (STI) management guidelines for use in primary care 2022 update. Sex Health. 2023 Feb;20(1):1-8. doi: 10.1071/SH22134. PMID: 36356948. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36356948/","Unemo M, Seifert HS, Hook EW 3rd, Hawkes S, Ndowa F, Dillon JR. Gonorrhoea. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019 Nov 21;5(1):79. doi: 10.1038/s41572-019-0128-6. PMID: 31754194. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31754194/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-20T16:02:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-20T16:02:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5091"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead